%I A392505 #75 Mar 29 2026 17:44:30
%S A392505 1,2,6,10,4,14,12,22,8,26,18,34,16,38,20,28,30,33,3,9,15,21,7,35,55,5,
%T A392505 25,65,39,13,91,42,44,40,46,23,69,24,57,19,95,45,51,17,85,50,52,56,58,
%U A392505 29,87,36,62,31,93,60,68,66,70,74,32,82,48,86,43,129,63,77
%N A392505 a(1) = 1, a(2) = 2; for n > 2, a(n) is the smallest unused number such that a(n) shares a factor with a(n-1) while rad(a(n)*a(n-1)) has not previously occurred as the rad value of the product of adjacent terms, where rad = A007947.
%C A392505 The distribution of terms in the sequence is very similar to the EKG sequence, see the attached image, although some terms are outliers and do not fall on the three dominant lines - these are due to the occurrence of semiprimes containing a large prime.
%C A392505 The vast majority of primes occur in their natural order, especially for large n, and, like the EKG sequence, they are preceded and followed by terms that are 2 and 3 times their value. Those that are not in natural order are preceded and followed by larger multiples.
%C A392505 In the first 500K terms there are no fixed points other than 1 and 2. The sequence is conjectured to be a permutation of the positive numbers.
%C A392505 See A393471 for the rad value of the product of adjacent terms.
%C A392505 The general pattern 2*p -> p -> 3*p is disturbed when 2*p follows 2^k for some k in this sequence. Entry of a(n) = m*p sometimes occurs when m | a(n-1), especially when m is prime. Examples: a(13) = 16, a(14) = 2*19, thus, a(39..41) = {3*19, 19, 5*19}; a(140) = 2^7, a(141) = 2*83 and a(235) = 3*83 following a product of 3, so a(386..388) = {5*83, 83, 7*83}. - _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 24 2026
%H A392505 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A392505/b392505.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 1..10000</a>
%H A392505 Michael De Vlieger, <a href="/A392505/a392505_1.png">Log log scatterplot of a(n)</a>, n = 1..2^14, showing primes in red, proper prime powers in gold, squarefree composites in green, powerful numbers that are not prime powers in purple, and numbers neither squarefree nor powerful in blue.
%H A392505 Scott R. Shannon, <a href="/A392505/a392505.png">Image of the first 100000 terms</a>. The colors are graduated across the spectrum from red to violet to show the number of prime factors of each term, counted with multiplicity. The thin green line is a(n) = n.
%e A392505 a(3) = 6 as the rad value for the product of previous adjacent terms is 2, so a(3) cannot be 4, as rad(2*4) = 2, while 6 shares a factor with 2 and rad(2*6) = 6.
%e A392505 a(4) = 10 as the rad values for the products of previous adjacent terms are 2 and 6, so a(4) cannot be 3, 4 or 8, while 10 shares a factor with 6 and rad(6*10) = 30.
%t A392505 Block[{c, q}, nn = 120; c[_] := False; q[_] := False; Set[{i, j}, {1, 2}]; u = 3; MapIndexed[Set[{c[#], q[#]}, {True, True}] &, {1, 2}]; rad[x_] := Times @@ FactorInteger[x][[All, 1]]; {i, j}~Join~Reap[Do[If[PrimePowerQ[j], p = FactorInteger[j][[1, 1]]; k = 1; While[Or[c[#], q[rad[j*#] ] ] &[p*k], k++]; k *= p, k = u; While[Or[c[k], q[rad[j*k] ], CoprimeQ[j, k] ], k++] ]; Sow[k]; Set[{q[rad[j*k] ], c[k], i, j}, {True, True, j, k}]; If[k == u, While[c[u], u++]], {n, 3, nn}] ][[-1, 1]] ] (* _Michael De Vlieger_, Mar 24 2026 *)
%Y A392505 Cf. A393471 (rad values), A007947, A064413, A372043.
